?TOP STORIES

TEXAS PUC RULES TO REVERSE UTILITIES STRANDED-COSTS EFFORTS

The Texas Public Utility Commission ruled Wednesday that TXU Electric & Gas, 
the state's largest electric utility, must return to ratepayers most of the 
$1.2 billion it has collected to offset expenses the company contends will be 
left "stranded" when electric retail competition debuts next year.

US FERC TO OK ORGANIZATION TO OVERSEE PACIFIC NW POWER GRID

Federal regulators Wednesday approved a plan to create a new entity to 
independently administer competitive access to the Pacific Northwest's power 
grid, which is dominated by the federally owned Bonneville Power 
Administration's transmission system.

SENATORS INTRODUCE BILL TO TEMPORARILY CAP ELECTRIC RATES IN WESTERN STATES

West Coast senators formally introduced legislation Tuesday to temporarily 
cap wholesale electric rates and expressed hope that their proposal to ease 
the huge run-up in energy prices might clear the committee and make it to a 
vote on the Senate floor.

CALIFORNIA APPROVES TWO 40-MW POWER PLANTS; ON GRID BY AUGUST 1

The California Energy Commission gave final approval to the construction of 
two 40-megawatt power plants in San Bernardino County, and the plants are 
expected to be fully operational no later than August 1.

ENERGY PLANT PROPOSED FOR SOUTH FULTON

An Oklahoma company wants to build an electric generating plant near Union 
City in south Fulton. Williams, an electrical company that produces and sells 
energy and related services, wants to build the plant on a 230-acre site on 
Peters Road off Ga. 138, just up the road from the Christian City community. 




